Derek Atkins (warlord@MIT.EDU) wrote:
: In article <2rg1tg$1dr@newshost.uni-koblenz.de> knight@flake.uni-koblenz.de (Rainer Schmitz) writes:

:    How can I factor a number?

:    The algorithm should be easy to understand and (of course) fast.

: No, it is not.  Factoring is a hard problem.  For example, RSA-129, a
: 129-decimal-digit RSA modulus (product of two large primes) took about
: 5000 MIPS-years of computing time to factor.

: If you want details of factoring, you can obtain the code that was
: used to help factor RSA-129 from
: 	ftp://toxicwaste.mit.edu/pub/rsa129/mpqs.tar.Z

: If you want the papers that go along with this, then try:
: 	ftp://toxicwaste.mit.edu/pub/rsa129/fact_by_email.Z
: or	ftp://toxicwaste.mit.edu/pub/rsa129/mpqs_sans_math.Z

: Hope this helps

: -derek
: --
:          Derek Atkins, SB '93 MIT EE, G MIT Media Laboratory
:        Member, MIT Student Information Processing Board (SIPB)
:     Home page: http://www.mit.edu:8001/people/warlord/home_page.html
:        warlord@MIT.EDU    PP-ASEL     N1NWH    PGP key available

Nonsense. Factorising is easy. It's doing it quickly that's hard.

JMcC 
